        <h2>Types of Insurance Relevant to College Students</h2>
        
        <h3>Health Insurance</h3>
        <p>Health insurance covers medical expenses, which can be significant without coverage. For college students, unexpected medical bills can be financially destabilizing. Many colleges offer health plans for students. Alternatively, students can remain on their parents' insurance until the age of 26, or consider individual health insurance plans. Having health insurance ensures access to necessary medical care without the burden of high costs.</p>
        
        <h3>Renters Insurance</h3>
        <p>Renters insurance provides coverage for your belongings in your dorm or apartment in case of theft, fire, or other damages. College students often underestimate the value of their possessions. Renters insurance is an affordable way to protect these assets. It can also cover additional living expenses if your rented space becomes uninhabitable due to covered events.</p>
        
        <h3>Auto Insurance</h3>
        <p>If you own or use a car on campus, auto insurance is a legal requirement. It covers damage to your vehicle and protects you against liability if you're involved in an accident. Auto insurance policies vary, but typically include coverage for collisions, personal injury, and liability. Students should look for policies that offer a balance between comprehensive coverage and affordable premiums.</p>
        
        <h3>Travel Insurance</h3>
        <p>For students planning to study abroad or travel, travel insurance can cover medical emergencies, trip cancellations, and lost baggage. It offers peace of mind when traveling, handling unexpected incidents that could otherwise be costly. Ensure to check the coverage details, as some policies provide additional benefits like 24/7 emergency assistance.</p>

